"\n"
"<p><span class=\"block-image image-wrapper\"><img alt=\"The kind (detail), Hyacinthe Rigaud, Louis XIV, 1701, oil on canvas, 9’2” x 6’3” (Musée du Louvre, Paris)\" src=\"https://ka-perseus-images.s3.amazonaws.com/35b070b91c7e222e787ee70184969e13d8c7fc77.jpg\" /><span class=\"image-caption\">The king(detail), Hyacinthe Rigaud, Louis XIV, 1701, oil on canvas, 9&rsquo;2&rdquo; x 6&rsquo;3&rdquo; (Mus&eacute;e du Louvre, Paris)</span></span></p>\n"
"\n"
"<p>Louis&rsquo; hair is also worth noting (and not just because it&rsquo;s amazing). To modern eyes, the king&rsquo;s hair seems more appropriate for a member of KISS than for a sixty-three year old absolute monarch; however, Louis&rsquo; hair cascades down his royal robes&mdash;representing a still youthful and robust king. In official royal portraits, there was constant negotiation between historical accuracy and the ideal form. How exactly to render Louis&rsquo; hair sparked an intense debate on more than one occasion: should the hairstyle be accurate, the king presented as he actually looks, or should concessions be made so that the regal qualities of the king might be more readily apparent? Like with Louis&rsquo; (lack of) height, royal painters had to strike a balance between an identifiable and recognizable portrait and one that idealized the sitter to meet the patron&rsquo;s desired result.&nbsp;</p>\n"
"\n"
"<p><span class=\"block-image image-wrapper\"><img alt=\"The king’s legs (detail), Hyacinthe Rigaud, Louis XIV, 1701, oil on canvas, 9’2” x 6’3” (Musée du Louvre, Paris)\" src=\"https://ka-perseus-images.s3.amazonaws.com/1a3804d1b5d20e72b3c5375dcba20de99434eb7f.jpg\" /><span class=\"image-caption\">The king&rsquo;s legs (detail), Hyacinthe Rigaud, <em>Louis XIV</em>, 1701, oil on canvas, 9&rsquo;2&rdquo; x 6&rsquo;3&rdquo; (Mus&eacute;e du Louvre, Paris)</span></span></p>\n"
"\n"
"<p>Similarly, Louis&rsquo; legs, which Rigaud has cleverly and prominently displayed, are rather well defined for an aging king. Louis&rsquo; advancing age (he would die fourteen years after this portrait) is betrayed by his lined face, slight jowls, and double chin; the king was reportedly in ill health and had to have several teeth extracted due to infection. It is no coincidence that Louis is posed with his majestic robe draped over his shoulder to reveal his lower limbs: Louis had been a ballet dancer in his youth and prided himself on his dancer&rsquo;s legs. The legs, while in contrast to his aged face, suggest a vital and vigorous man, still in the prime of his power. Rigaud tempers the monarch&rsquo;s timeworn face by reminding the viewer of Louis&rsquo; athletic past; the heeled shoes are not only flattering but add several precious inches onto Louis&rsquo; height. Here, Louis is identifiable&mdash;clearly the portrait is of the king in the later years of his life&mdash;yet also idealized, his well-toned legs and lustrous hair preternaturally preserved.</p>\n"
"\n"
"<h3>Success&nbsp;</h3>\n"
"\n"
"<p>Rigaud&rsquo;s portrait, originally commissioned as a gift for Louis&rsquo; grandson, Philip V of Spain, was so well received that Louis ultimately chose to keep it and sent a copy in its place. Rigaud&nbsp;so successfully captured power of&nbsp;Louis XIV that the image was placed over the throne and in the king&rsquo;s absence, the painting served as his proxy and courtiers were forbidden to turn their backs on the painting.&nbsp;</p>\n"
"\n"
