"<p>This, of course, is impossible to prove or disprove. What is more challenging is Boime&rsquo;s general criticisms of early psychiatry which, he argues, by classifying, containing and observing people was effective only in silencing the voices of the mentally ill, rendering them invisible and therefore subject to abuse. The fact that the sitters of the paintings are given no names, but are defined only by their illnesses would seem to confirm this view and, for that reason, many modern viewers of the paintings do feel disconcerted when looking at them.&nbsp;</p>\n"
"\n"
"<h3><span>The Portraits</span></h3>\n"
"\n"
"<p><span>​The five surviving portraits are bust length and in front view, without hands.&nbsp;The canvases vary in dimensions but the heads are all close to life-size.&nbsp;The five surviving portraits are bust length and in front view, without hands.&nbsp;</span></p>\n"
"\n"
"<p>&nbsp;<span class=\"image-wrapper inline-image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ka-perseus-images.s3.amazonaws.com/3e5237809c7828b9f81856d8e776a734e087f8a4.jpg\" /><span class=\"image-caption\">Th&eacute;odore G&eacute;ricault, <em>Portrait of a Kleptomaniac</em>, 1822, oil on canvas, 61 x 50 cm (Museum of Fine Arts, Ghent)</span></span>The canvases vary in dimensions but the heads are all close to life-size. The viewpoint is at eye level for the three men but from above for the women, indicating that the paintings were executed in different places.&nbsp;It seems likely that the women were painted in the women&rsquo;s hospital Salp&ecirc;tri&egrave;re, while the men were selected from among the inmates of Charenton and Bicȇtre. &nbsp;None of the sitters is named; they are identified by their malady. None look directly at the viewer, contributing to an uneasy sense of distractedness in their gazes that can be read as stillness, as though they are lost in their own thoughts, or as disconnectedness from the process in which they are involved. These are not patrons and have had no say in how they are depicted.&nbsp;</p>\n"
"\n"
"<p>Each is shown in three-quarter profile, some to the left, some to the right. The pose is typical of formal, honorific portraits, effecting a restrained composition that does not make it apparent that they are confined in asylums. There is no evidence of the setting in the backgrounds either, which are cast in shadow, as are most of their bodies, drawing the focus largely on their faces.</p>\n"
"\n"
"<p>&nbsp;<span class=\"image-wrapper inline-image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ka-perseus-images.s3.amazonaws.com/9286354ca86163fdd2edd4de1bb38c725452ba7d.jpg\" /><span class=\"image-caption\">Th&eacute;odore G&eacute;ricault, <em>Portrait of a Man Suffering from Delusions of Military Command</em>, 1822, oil on canvas, 81 x 65 cm (Sammlung Oskar Reinhart, Winterthur)</span></span>The dark coloring creates a sombre atmosphere, evocative of brooding introspection.&nbsp;Their clothing lends them a degree of personal dignity, giving no indication as to the nature of their conditions, the one exception being the man suffering from delusions of military grandeur who wears a medallion on his chest, a tasseled hat and a cloak over one shoulder, which point to his delusions. The medallion has no shine to it and the string that it hangs from looks makeshift and worn.&nbsp;</p>\n"
"\n"
"<p>The paintings were executed with great speed, entirely from life and probably in one sitting. &nbsp;Critics often remark on the painterly quality of the work, the extraordinary fluency of brushwork, in contrast with G&eacute;ricault&rsquo;s early more sculptural style, suggesting that the erratic brushwork is used to mirror the disordered thoughts of the patients. In places it is applied in almost translucent layers, while in others it is thicker creating highly expressive contrasts in textures.</p>\n"
"\n"
"<h3>Romantic Scientists</h3>\n"
"\n"
"<p>What perhaps strikes one most about the portraits is the extraordinary empathy we are made to feel for these poor souls, who might not strike us immediately as insane, but who certainly exhibit outward signs of inward suffering.</p>\n"
"\n"
"<p>&nbsp;<span class=\"image-wrapper inline-image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ka-perseus-images.s3.amazonaws.com/29254bf217f00cad67131eeb7e9f56b97a82a7be.jpg\" /><span class=\"image-caption\">John Constable, Cloud Study, 1822, oil on paper laid on board, 47.6 x 57.5 cm (Tate Britain)&nbsp;</span></span>In bringing the sensitivity of a great artist to assist scientific enquiry, G&eacute;ricault was not alone among Romantic painters. John Constable&rsquo;s cloud studies, for example, were exactly contemporary with the portraits and provide an interesting parallel. &nbsp;</p>\n"
"\n"
"<p>Both artists capture brilliantly the fleeting moment, the shifting movements in Constable&rsquo;s cumulus, stratus, cirrus and nimbus, in G&eacute;ricault the complex play of emotions on the faces of the insane.</p>\n"
"\n"
"<p>Not since the Renaissance has art illustrated so beautifully the concerns of the scientific domain; in G&eacute;ricault&rsquo;s case teaching those early psychiatrists, we might be tempted to think, to look on their patients with a more human gaze.</p>\n"
"\n"
