"<h3>The way of the flesh and the way of the spirit</h3>\n"
"\n"
"<p>The Dutch painter Pieter Aertsen, who worked for many years in Antwerp, was later renowned for his life-size market scenes with exuberant still life elements. Many scholars have commented on the bold originality of Aertsen&rsquo;s compositions, and rightly so. In the sixteenth century, religious or mythological scenes usually occupied pride of place in works of art, while everyday objects were considered mere accessories. In this and other&nbsp;roughly contemporary works like <em>Christ in the House of Mary and Martha</em>&nbsp;(below), Aertsen has deliberately reversed this formula. He gave all the attention to the accessories, which seem to spill out of the picture and into the viewer&rsquo;s own space.</p>\n"
"\n"
"<p><span class=\"block-image image-wrapper\"><img alt=\"Pieter Aertsen, Christ with Mary and Martha, 1552, 101.5 x 60 cm (Kunsthistorisches Museum, Vienna)\" src=\"https://ka-perseus-images.s3.amazonaws.com/ccc4b4ff34ac21f9c91e6a330370a3d1f5382ac0.jpg\" /><span class=\"image-caption\">Pieter Aertsen, <em>Christ in the House of&nbsp;Mary and Martha</em>, 1552, 101.5 x 60 cm (Kunsthistorisches Museum, Vienna)</span></span></p>\n"
"\n"
